AppLocker is an application control technology built into Windows to prevent users from running applications not approved by policy
each policy contains one or more enforcement rules, and each rule contains a permission and a condition
    permissions define the action (allow or deny) and the user/group to which the rule applies
    conditions define the rule itself, can be based on published, path, and/or file hash
these policies are defined by system admins and deployed via GPOs or Intune

enumeration of policies
    via registry
        useful when we already have console access to a protected machine
            PS C:\Users\pchilds> Get-ChildItem 'HKLM:Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\SrpV2'
            PS C:\Users\pchilds> Get-ChildItem 'HKLM:Software\Policies\Microsoft\Windows\SrpV2\Exe'
    native applocker cmdlet
        PS C:\Users\pchilds> $policy = Get-AppLockerPolicy -Effective
        PS C:\Users\pchilds> $policy.RuleCollections
    via GPOs
        useful when we have a beacon running on an unprotected machine, and trying to move laterally to protected machine
        we can walk through each container in SYSVOL and look for Registry.pol in the Machine dir
             beacon> ldapsearch (objectClass=groupPolicyContainer) --attributes displayName,gPCFileSysPath
                --------------------
                displayName: AppLocker
                gPCFileSysPath: \\contoso.com\SysVol\contoso.com\Policies\{8ECEE926-7FEE-48CD-9F51-493EB5AD95DC}
                --------------------
            beacon> ls \\contoso.com\SysVol\contoso.com\Policies\{8ECEE926-7FEE-48CD-9F51-493EB5AD95DC}\Machine
            beacon> download \\contoso.com\SysVol\contoso.com\Policies\{8ECEE926-7FEE-48CD-9F51-493EB5AD95DC}\Machine\Registry.pol
        once we sync the file to our desktop we can read using parse-polfile cmdlet
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> Parse-PolFile -Path .\Desktop\Registry.pol

